1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:27,827
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:27,806 --> 00:00:32,713
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:40,442 --> 00:00:56,902
On one of the Tuesday evenings, one of the people who came along told us this tale of a six-year-old child who was playing a game and then suddenly said to her mother, there's no reason for being, and then went back playing.

4
00:00:59,616 --> 00:01:00,378
Six years old.

5
00:01:03,722 --> 00:01:10,871
So this being, she must have, I suppose, heard her parents talk about it or friends about the meaning of life and all that.

6
00:01:11,993 --> 00:01:16,200
And it must have sort of worked on her mind.

7
00:01:17,141 --> 00:01:27,295
She must have understood what she was saying because how can you come out with something like that without having some inkling, some feel for what you actually mean?

8
00:01:28,878 --> 00:01:31,284
And the interesting thing is that, of course, he was playing.

9
00:01:31,686 --> 00:01:36,358
So the thing about play, isn't it, is that you do it for yourself.

10
00:01:36,418 --> 00:01:37,661
You don't do it for any other reason.

11
00:01:37,861 --> 00:01:41,992
You don't play Monopoly to make yourself famous while I'm there.

12
00:01:43,272 --> 00:01:46,376
I mean, it's like a game is just a game.

13
00:01:46,477 --> 00:01:51,984
I mean, I know that we put a lot of things on games these days, like football, you know, it's become an industry.

14
00:01:52,626 --> 00:01:59,036
But when a child plays a game, or when we ourselves play a game with a child, we're just playing a game.

15
00:01:59,617 --> 00:02:03,522
It doesn't have any objective apart from just playing the game.

16
00:02:05,265 --> 00:02:09,110
And therefore, all your attention is in, you know, just that doing.

17
00:02:10,829 --> 00:02:13,832
I think the second quality is, of course, it's very joyful, isn't it?

18
00:02:14,173 --> 00:02:20,181
It's a sort of a happy thing to do, playing a game, playing cards.

19
00:02:21,883 --> 00:02:30,014
And I think as adults we might have things like hobbies, which don't particularly have any reason beyond themselves.

20
00:02:30,133 --> 00:02:31,756
They're just something you like to do.

21
00:02:32,957 --> 00:02:38,625
They don't have any aim or objective beyond just that doing.

22
00:02:39,382 --> 00:02:43,668
And usually, a person would say that they enjoy their hobby.

23
00:02:44,028 --> 00:02:47,633
It wouldn't make sense to have a hobby that you didn't enjoy.

24
00:02:47,653 --> 00:02:56,366
So if you cook, for instance, if you like cooking, you do it just for the pleasure of it, you know.

25
00:02:56,627 --> 00:02:57,990
And then you might share it with friends.

26
00:02:59,231 --> 00:03:02,156
And you might lose a few friends, but it's a joyful occasion.

27
00:03:02,216 --> 00:03:05,540
It's something that you've enjoyed doing, you see.

28
00:03:08,743 --> 00:03:14,094
So this little girl she's playing with, there's no reason for being.

29
00:03:14,215 --> 00:03:17,320
So it depends, of course, what we mean by reason.

30
00:03:20,266 --> 00:03:30,347
If we mean by reason that there's some other, something outside the game, something outside we're doing, we're sort of aiming at some future result.

31
00:03:30,681 --> 00:03:36,110
some end point that we're moving towards, then that puts a pressure, doesn't it?

32
00:03:36,131 --> 00:03:45,665
It puts a pressure on what you're doing now, because what you're doing now is not in itself entire and whole.

33
00:03:46,045 --> 00:03:51,474
The action is not completed until some future event arises.

34
00:03:52,618 --> 00:04:01,554
So these professional games, you know, these footballers and tennis players, sure, they play the game, but it's not just a game, is it?

35
00:04:01,693 --> 00:04:02,474
There's something else.

36
00:04:02,534 --> 00:04:03,856
There's an ambition about it.

37
00:04:04,277 --> 00:04:06,662
There's the climbing up the ladder of success.

38
00:04:06,701 --> 00:04:07,342
There's the money.

39
00:04:08,243 --> 00:04:15,956
So the game itself now doesn't have that immediate sense of perfect joy that a game might have for a child.

40
00:04:16,778 --> 00:04:18,440
It's now got a pressure on it, hasn't it?

41
00:04:29,456 --> 00:04:32,682
Now as opposed to this word being, we've got this other word becoming.

42
00:04:34,144 --> 00:04:41,536
And the word in the Pali for that is bhāva, to become.

43
00:04:41,557 --> 00:04:55,060
So when the Buddha describes this process of becoming, he really describes it quite clearly in the Dependence Origination, which is what we'll chant tomorrow, the sequence of mental events.

44
00:05:00,067 --> 00:05:17,942
And somewhere, somewhere in that process of play, see, which sort of ends around about the age of seven or so, when we lose that immediate innocence of life, and thought comes in, you see, and thought launches us out into some future.

45
00:05:18,764 --> 00:05:22,752
We've lived long enough to imagine a future, see, just a

46
00:05:23,137 --> 00:05:27,021
How futuristic can a child of three be?

47
00:05:27,701 --> 00:05:32,709
What does it mean to a child of three to say that in two months' time there'll be Christmas?

48
00:05:34,170 --> 00:05:37,334
They don't live that long to understand what two months is, really.

49
00:05:37,514 --> 00:05:40,637
It's sort of an imaginative thing.

50
00:05:40,658 --> 00:05:47,446
But for us, having lived so long, we begin to project, don't we?

51
00:05:48,146 --> 00:05:48,908
We sort of know

52
00:05:50,812 --> 00:05:51,593
We know where we're going.

53
00:05:51,612 --> 00:05:53,035
We've got an idea of time.

54
00:05:53,375 --> 00:05:54,737
It's all blocked out for us.

55
00:06:02,567 --> 00:06:08,074
So now somewhere, somewhere in that process, something goes wrong.

56
00:06:09,475 --> 00:06:14,963
Now as opposed to that, as opposed to that going wrong and living for some future event,

57
00:06:15,701 --> 00:06:20,088
You have the Buddha or the enlightened ones who don't do that, but they're still living in time.

58
00:06:20,108 --> 00:06:21,189
They know what two months is.

59
00:06:22,851 --> 00:06:24,733
They also have a clear idea of time.

60
00:06:27,057 --> 00:06:28,238
But somehow they don't suffer.

61
00:06:28,379 --> 00:06:32,084
Somehow they don't get this comeback which is in the process of becoming.

62
00:06:36,589 --> 00:06:37,490
In the...

63
00:06:39,293 --> 00:06:47,482
In the law of karma, when they talk about, when Buddhism talks about karma, it talks about two types of karma, kusala and akusala.

64
00:06:47,502 --> 00:06:55,990
So this translates as wholesome, unwholesome actions, virtuous and unvirtuous actions, skillful and unskillful actions.

65
00:06:56,831 --> 00:06:58,052
That's how you can translate it.

66
00:07:00,074 --> 00:07:07,983
But interestingly enough, when they try to describe or when they try to find a word for an enlightened person doing an action,

67
00:07:09,112 --> 00:07:18,661
they sort of use another word, kriya, which is translated in a funny way as functional, functional action.

68
00:07:22,964 --> 00:07:28,831
So there's something distinctive between somebody who is fully liberated and somebody who isn't.

69
00:07:31,353 --> 00:07:32,814
It's a sort of sharp line.

70
00:07:32,875 --> 00:07:34,475
It's not as though it's a progression.

71
00:07:34,757 --> 00:07:37,278
You either are liberated or you're not.

72
00:07:37,916 --> 00:07:40,740
You might be a little bit liberated, but you're not fully liberated.

73
00:07:40,779 --> 00:07:46,607
There's always that peculiar way of looking at things which causes some form of dissatisfaction.

74
00:07:51,331 --> 00:07:57,559
So what is it that goes wrong within that process which causes us to become rather than to be?

75
00:08:00,541 --> 00:08:03,384
So when the Buddha is deciding to teach,

76
00:08:05,625 --> 00:08:12,274
And that comes out of just the desire to share the goodness that he's discovered.

77
00:08:14,737 --> 00:08:16,641
It's a natural thing, isn't it?

78
00:08:17,802 --> 00:08:23,870
They say in Zen, for instance, that out of wisdom, compassion arises naturally, love arises naturally.

79
00:08:25,791 --> 00:08:29,399
And there's some teachers in Zen that won't touch practices like loving-kindness.

80
00:08:29,658 --> 00:08:32,764
It's off the path.

81
00:08:32,784 --> 00:08:43,245
You want to get to the enlightenment, to the awakening, and then everything else just happens naturally.

82
00:08:43,264 --> 00:08:48,475
So when the Buddha was awakened and this natural desire came to teach,

83
00:08:49,940 --> 00:08:51,602
And he thought, well, who could he teach?

84
00:08:51,702 --> 00:09:13,803
And having understood or come to know that his two teachers, those were his first people he thought he might help, were dead, he then walks to find his other five companions, those who had told him he'd gone soft and they didn't want to know him anymore because he'd had this rice pudding, if you remember.

85
00:09:17,345 --> 00:09:25,177
And he walks from where he becomes enlightened, where he becomes awakened in Bodh Gaya, he walks all the way to Sanat in...

86
00:09:26,508 --> 00:09:33,315
Now I've got this figure of 400 miles, but I don't think that's quite right, but it's a heck of a long way anyway.

87
00:09:36,057 --> 00:09:37,178
It's five hours on the train.

88
00:09:37,558 --> 00:09:38,940
Yeah, it's five hours on the train.

89
00:09:39,441 --> 00:09:41,001
I remember that.

90
00:09:41,022 --> 00:09:42,864
So it's quite a long way.

91
00:09:42,984 --> 00:09:45,846
So he's off, and he has to ask.

92
00:09:45,907 --> 00:09:48,330
It's not as though people have got mobiles in those days.

93
00:09:49,671 --> 00:09:50,552
They'll find out where they are.

94
00:09:52,953 --> 00:09:55,856
And then he begins to teach, and...

95
00:09:57,337 --> 00:10:21,642
Throughout his career as a teacher, he says when somebody comes to him who doesn't accept what he's saying, like there's an occasion when this fellow called Dandapani, which means stick in hand, must have been a nickname, comes and asks him what he teaches, and the Buddha says what he teaches, and he goes away clicking his tongue, you know, shaking his head, a lot of rubbish, you know.

96
00:10:23,679 --> 00:10:35,513
In fact, there's a lovely incident when he starts off on the teaching to find his five companions and he comes across an ascetic who sort of sees a certain glow around him, a certain brightness.

97
00:10:35,572 --> 00:10:37,414
And he says, my, he says, you're bright.

98
00:10:37,434 --> 00:10:38,456
He says, who's your teacher?

99
00:10:39,037 --> 00:10:44,322
And he launches into this sort of self-panegyric about him saying, you know, I am the fully enlightened one.

100
00:10:44,363 --> 00:10:45,783
I don't need to teach lots of stuff.

101
00:10:46,044 --> 00:10:49,148
And the guy sort of says, oh, right, OK. And so on.

102
00:10:49,128 --> 00:11:11,220
sort of wanders off and I think that was a sort of an early lesson that that's not what you do if you're going to teach and when people don't accept his teaching he says he's not saddened by it he's not upset by it and yet when people do accept his teachings he's joyful

103
00:11:14,710 --> 00:11:26,182
And when he describes the Buddha heart, when he describes how he experiences Nibbāna as this present experience, he talks about it being contented and with it happy.

104
00:11:28,164 --> 00:11:29,386
Contented and with it happy.

105
00:11:32,490 --> 00:11:42,961
And those four limitables, love, compassion, joy, equanimity, but especially the first three, which is about relationship, love, compassion and joy, are

106
00:11:44,663 --> 00:11:52,514
Those contain, as it were, in their various shades, the way the Buddha heart actually responds to the world.

107
00:11:53,115 --> 00:12:01,609
And if he's on his own, if he's quiet, or an enlightened person's quiet, they just fall into this state of equanimity.

108
00:12:08,677 --> 00:12:28,524
So you get the sort of sense that somebody who's awakened is living very much in the present moment, doesn't have any particular aim, he's just responding from that wisdom point to a given situation now, without any care for future results.

109
00:12:32,403 --> 00:12:49,272
Even when he goes to begin his teaching and men and women approach him to join him, he doesn't seem to have any particular idea of where the order is going.

110
00:12:50,134 --> 00:12:55,001
He's just following the general customs of ascetics in those days.

111
00:12:55,825 --> 00:13:05,557
And it's only as things go wrong, as certain monks and nuns make mistakes or do something wrong, that he produces a rule.

112
00:13:07,461 --> 00:13:16,552
And in the end, by the end of his life, he's produced all these rules and it rests on a particular platform of understanding.

113
00:13:16,952 --> 00:13:19,235
That's what you would call an institution, isn't it?

114
00:13:19,456 --> 00:13:20,398
An institution is...

115
00:13:21,796 --> 00:13:47,533
a given reason some sort of platform and then you build up a rule around it to give it some sort of I want a better word legal solidity so even say marriage that's an institution isn't it marriage just between two people so there's a basic understanding and then there are rules spoken or unspoken which maintain that particular relationship

116
00:13:50,888 --> 00:13:52,791
And he ends up with that.

117
00:13:54,513 --> 00:14:08,914
Not that he had any specific idea as to where it was going, but by the end of his life he can look back and think, well, yeah, what's been produced or what's happened is good.

118
00:14:10,376 --> 00:14:17,368
He talks about the four sanghas or the four assemblies, monks and nuns, laywomen and laymen.

119
00:14:17,871 --> 00:14:19,293
But that sort of happened naturally.

120
00:14:19,453 --> 00:14:26,620
He didn't seem to have gone out particularly to establish that.

121
00:14:26,961 --> 00:14:31,066
It just happened as he's walking around and people join him, etc., etc.

122
00:14:33,727 --> 00:14:43,879
So you get the sense of spontaneity rather than knee-jerk reactions or some sort of

123
00:14:45,479 --> 00:15:14,777
preconditioned idea as to where he's going so that's another quality isn't it of play it's spontaneous a child is very spontaneous all that perhaps we can talk about a sense of just being in the moment moving from one moment to the next responding to it with wisdom

124
00:15:16,647 --> 00:15:32,335
without any sense of some future success, success and failure, all that's out the window, without any sense of gain, riches or anything like that, without any sense of power, wanting to control.

125
00:15:32,375 --> 00:15:39,668
He didn't particularly want to control monks and nuns.

126
00:15:41,302 --> 00:15:50,099
He just wanted to set up a situation where eventually all they could do was meditate and study the Dharma.

127
00:15:50,178 --> 00:15:54,267
That's the two duties that he put to the monks.

128
00:15:54,287 --> 00:16:01,520
And he set up certain institutions for lay people by taking refugees to five precepts and general guidelines.

129
00:16:16,638 --> 00:16:27,154
So there's no sense of him wanting to be rich, to be powerful, to be successful in any sense.

130
00:16:30,139 --> 00:16:31,903
He's not driven by some future aim.

131
00:16:33,125 --> 00:16:42,460
And he's not worried about being famous.

132
00:16:43,164 --> 00:16:49,278
There's no hint in the scriptures that he gets upset if people don't recognize him.

133
00:16:49,759 --> 00:17:00,481
In fact, there's a point there where a monk or somebody enters into a small congregation of monks and they ask, well, which one is the Bhagavad?

134
00:17:00,461 --> 00:17:05,792
So he hasn't got a special hat on, or three stripes on his shoulders.

135
00:17:09,079 --> 00:17:10,343
He's just an ordinary person.

136
00:17:11,064 --> 00:17:15,032
He just looks like he doesn't try to lift himself above others.

137
00:17:18,700 --> 00:17:20,984
All these, all these sort of...

138
00:17:22,061 --> 00:17:25,345
are manifesting a relationship.

139
00:17:25,644 --> 00:17:26,205
That's what they're doing.

140
00:17:26,226 --> 00:17:35,934
They're manifesting a relationship with what happens, a relationship with time, a relationship with their life.

141
00:17:37,715 --> 00:17:41,819
The question of what am I supposed to be doing or where am I supposed to be going or why am I here?

142
00:17:42,381 --> 00:17:43,240
Why am I here?

143
00:17:43,421 --> 00:17:43,961
Who am I?

144
00:17:44,962 --> 00:17:46,443
See, all those questions have disappeared.

145
00:17:46,463 --> 00:17:49,487
There is just this moment of

146
00:17:50,547 --> 00:17:54,013
this relationship and this response, coming from the point of wisdom.

147
00:17:58,102 --> 00:18:10,345
In that moment there's that complete openness to it, because there's nothing negative within the person, something that has to be hidden or repressed,

148
00:18:10,544 --> 00:18:15,551
you know, some little dislike or guilt or whatever, the usual gamut of human misery.

149
00:18:15,571 --> 00:18:20,459
Because there's nothing that there, there's that ability just to be completely open to the situation.

150
00:18:21,480 --> 00:18:26,689
And whatever the situation presents, there's just coming out from the heart of wisdom.

151
00:18:31,214 --> 00:18:34,881
When it comes to, say, certain incidents like...

152
00:18:36,615 --> 00:18:42,583
the woman who comes crazed with grief because she's lost her child, her dead.

153
00:18:42,663 --> 00:18:48,970
She's got this idea that these ascetics are magic, have some magic, some mystical powers.

154
00:18:50,050 --> 00:19:00,362
And in her grief-stricken situation, the Buddha is able to say, he's able to realize that, well, to give her the straight teaching is just going to send her off berserk.

155
00:19:01,387 --> 00:19:06,496
He gives a little trick, you know, to come to realize the way life is.

156
00:19:08,598 --> 00:19:11,984
So he sends it off, doesn't he, to find a mustard seed.

157
00:19:12,525 --> 00:19:14,848
So mustard seeds are a million a penny.

158
00:19:15,931 --> 00:19:18,654
But he says, you must get it from a house where there's not been any death.

159
00:19:19,968 --> 00:19:22,590
So off she goes, you know, desperate, knocking on doors.

160
00:19:23,112 --> 00:19:23,952
You go, I must have seen it.

161
00:19:23,972 --> 00:19:24,413
Well, of course.

162
00:19:24,614 --> 00:19:25,214
Anybody died?

163
00:19:25,535 --> 00:19:25,815
Of course.

164
00:19:27,257 --> 00:19:35,146
And by the end of a certain sequence of hours, there comes this dawning, dawning, you see, that, well, death is part of life.

165
00:19:35,247 --> 00:19:35,988
It just happens.

166
00:19:36,288 --> 00:19:36,989
That's the way it is.

167
00:19:37,930 --> 00:19:41,914
So she comes back, you know, more balanced of mind.

168
00:19:42,635 --> 00:19:44,018
And then she's open to the teachings.

169
00:19:45,230 --> 00:19:51,796
And as all these stories go, he enters the order and becomes fully awakened.

170
00:19:57,842 --> 00:20:14,798
So he's able to respond easily to people because he's not coming from a fixed place, a fixed point, a presumption, a view, an opinion,

171
00:20:16,803 --> 00:20:38,457
This idea of being totally receptive means that you've got to come from the ability to receive different perspectives and bring them into your general way of seeing things.

172
00:20:43,229 --> 00:20:45,893
A perspective suggests that you're not holding on to it.

173
00:20:46,473 --> 00:21:00,714
You recognize that there are other perspectives, that you're prepared to have your perspective widened or broadened or somehow changed because you hear other people's views, their perspectives.

174
00:21:02,837 --> 00:21:06,402
But the word opinion gives us the idea that, well, you know, this is right, nobody else is wrong.

175
00:21:07,403 --> 00:21:10,507
It immediately closes you off, immediately shuts you off.

176
00:21:12,249 --> 00:21:14,510
It makes the relationship difficult.

177
00:21:14,530 --> 00:21:18,395
You're immediately in contradiction with somebody else who has a different opinion.

178
00:21:21,880 --> 00:21:30,028
So when somebody comes to the Buddha and asks him to give a teaching, he never goes into his teaching.

179
00:21:30,048 --> 00:21:31,089
He always says, well, what do you think?

180
00:21:32,655 --> 00:21:35,001
And then the person says what they think.

181
00:21:35,021 --> 00:21:36,505
And then he undermines their position.

182
00:21:38,450 --> 00:21:39,511
Bit of a trick, really, I suppose.

183
00:21:40,714 --> 00:21:44,785
And then when they're completely floored and completely lost, he says, well, now this is the truth.

184
00:21:44,865 --> 00:21:45,405
And off he goes.

185
00:21:49,174 --> 00:21:51,339
But he's not...

186
00:21:52,061 --> 00:21:56,646
He doesn't seem to have been that sort of person who said, well, look, you know, if you come to me, this is what it is, you know.

187
00:21:57,007 --> 00:21:58,909
If you don't accept it, you know, go away.

188
00:21:58,929 --> 00:22:06,938
He's prepared to try and understand where that person's coming from, and in so doing, to show that maybe they haven't got it quite right.

189
00:22:11,403 --> 00:22:14,286
And then there's an openness to the Dharma, that's what it says.

190
00:22:14,425 --> 00:22:20,112
Then there's a subtleness, there's a malleability in that person's mind, and that's when he offers the Dharma, you see.

191
00:22:26,015 --> 00:22:33,144
So we can see that just in general all these qualities are about being very present.

192
00:22:34,988 --> 00:22:36,470
Like a child is with play.

193
00:22:39,074 --> 00:22:54,856
There's nothing being deposited onto this present moment either by way of some past opinion, some opinion, some view that we've held onto from the past and that we must see this present moment through.

194
00:22:57,570 --> 00:23:02,278
There's no launching of this present moment into some future successful result.

195
00:23:02,919 --> 00:23:06,845
So it remains just entire and whole in itself.

196
00:23:06,924 --> 00:23:09,648
And you're sort of moving through time in these little blocks.

197
00:23:12,192 --> 00:23:13,354
But you're not coming from nowhere.

198
00:23:13,374 --> 00:23:14,796
That's the point.

199
00:23:15,076 --> 00:23:16,858
The Buddha's not coming from a blank sheet.

200
00:23:17,420 --> 00:23:24,269
He's coming from a specific way of relating to the world, which brings with it a specific understanding of

201
00:23:31,337 --> 00:23:35,423
So now as opposed to that, you've got this becoming, which is generally speaking what we do.

202
00:23:36,785 --> 00:23:37,445
This becoming.

203
00:23:38,467 --> 00:23:40,569
What's the core of the becoming?

204
00:23:40,829 --> 00:23:48,921
How do these opinions and views and futures and fame and riches and power, from where do they spring?

205
00:23:49,401 --> 00:23:51,042
Around what do they coagulate?

206
00:23:53,346 --> 00:23:54,887
What are they an expression of?

207
00:23:56,830 --> 00:23:58,492
So this is what the Buddha refers to as the self.

208
00:24:00,650 --> 00:24:01,832
And the self isn't a thing.

209
00:24:01,971 --> 00:24:06,559
It's not that you can point to it or pick it up or say what it is.

210
00:24:07,181 --> 00:24:07,942
It's a relationship.

211
00:24:08,301 --> 00:24:09,084
It's a relationship.

212
00:24:13,530 --> 00:24:18,439
So it's a mistake that we make, which is completely understandable.

213
00:24:18,519 --> 00:24:20,362
It's not as though it's a culpable mistake.

214
00:24:20,461 --> 00:24:24,208
We're not supposed to go beating ourselves around the head because we made this mistake.

215
00:24:25,069 --> 00:24:27,113
Because we come from a point of not knowing.

216
00:24:38,804 --> 00:24:54,229
There's a film called Zenoir, and there's a nice little passage in that where the master is asked by this person, what happens when you die?

217
00:24:54,910 --> 00:24:55,711
And he says, don't know.

218
00:24:57,394 --> 00:24:58,875
And then he says, why don't you know?

219
00:24:58,895 --> 00:24:59,917
He says, I'm not dead yet.

220
00:25:02,851 --> 00:25:18,127
It's like, you know, it's creating, it's sort of recognizing that what we've done is we've made a presumption, we've fallen into some sort of what the Buddha called a delusion.

221
00:25:20,130 --> 00:25:26,917
And a delusion, by definition, is something that you don't know you're deluded about, or else you wouldn't be deluded.

222
00:25:31,993 --> 00:25:35,459
So there we are, there we are, this little bundle of flesh and bones.

223
00:25:37,342 --> 00:25:37,923
And what do we know?

224
00:25:38,963 --> 00:25:39,424
What do we know?

225
00:25:43,711 --> 00:25:46,955
And then society comes at us with definitions, gives us a name.

226
00:25:48,298 --> 00:25:50,060
Parents tells us this and tells us that.

227
00:25:50,701 --> 00:25:52,805
We pick up the history, we get a language.

228
00:25:52,984 --> 00:25:54,406
Everything's sort of dumped on us, you know.

229
00:25:55,909 --> 00:26:00,516
So is it any wonder that we should end up thinking, well, this is what I am.

230
00:26:02,638 --> 00:26:12,189
And this is what I am, you see.

231
00:26:12,509 --> 00:26:12,970
I am.

232
00:26:12,990 --> 00:26:15,031
I am English.

233
00:26:15,553 --> 00:26:17,213
I am a teacher.

234
00:26:17,454 --> 00:26:17,934
I am.

235
00:26:17,954 --> 00:26:19,195
I am.

236
00:26:19,356 --> 00:26:20,417
This am business.

237
00:26:20,518 --> 00:26:28,326
This I with its definition, with its being, you might say.

238
00:26:29,285 --> 00:26:39,240
with its sense of self in all those definitions that we have about who we are and what we are.

239
00:26:39,260 --> 00:26:46,332
So once we've cornered ourselves, once we've gathered all these definitions about ourselves, you can see how it becomes an imprisonment.

240
00:26:48,758 --> 00:26:56,849
And you get these wonderful statements like, the one I love is, you know, if I did that, that wouldn't be me.

241
00:26:58,952 --> 00:27:00,996
If I thought that, that wouldn't be me.

242
00:27:01,576 --> 00:27:05,762
And it's a sort of a, you can feel the sort of clampness of that.

243
00:27:05,823 --> 00:27:12,993
You know, it's like something that's so tight, you know, about who I am.

244
00:27:15,303 --> 00:27:18,386
Now this who I am produces a doing.

245
00:27:18,867 --> 00:27:21,951
You walk into life with who I am and you start doing something.

246
00:27:23,032 --> 00:27:26,497
So I mean very simply, if you say I am a teacher, then you have to teach.

247
00:27:30,162 --> 00:27:34,907
But this teaching now isn't like the Buddha's teaching where he's just in relationship.

248
00:27:35,429 --> 00:27:36,830
It falls back on a definition.

249
00:27:37,191 --> 00:27:38,593
It falls back on who I am.

250
00:27:39,413 --> 00:27:40,955
So if I lose my job, who am I?

251
00:27:43,248 --> 00:27:44,308
then I get the depression.

252
00:27:45,431 --> 00:27:52,480
I mean, losing your job is bad enough to lose the income.

253
00:27:52,840 --> 00:27:53,501
That's bad enough.

254
00:27:54,743 --> 00:27:58,469
But then to lose a definition of yourself, well, that's an identity crisis.

255
00:27:59,009 --> 00:28:03,976
You might go around saying, well, I was a teacher, which is a bit of a downer.

256
00:28:05,278 --> 00:28:05,458
But

257
00:28:07,700 --> 00:28:17,813
But that business of identity creates a whole psychology of what we mean by an attachment.

258
00:28:27,226 --> 00:28:33,453
Now, of course, it goes deeper than that because at the deepest level we think we're humans.

259
00:28:34,462 --> 00:28:35,663
I am a human being.

260
00:28:35,963 --> 00:28:39,166
That's a pretty general statement most people on earth would agree with.

261
00:28:39,367 --> 00:28:40,147
I am a human being.

262
00:28:41,028 --> 00:28:43,090
But when you say, I am a human being, what do you mean?

263
00:28:43,592 --> 00:28:44,291
Are you the body?

264
00:28:46,473 --> 00:28:51,338
If you say, well, I am the body, I am this body, how long are you this body for?

265
00:28:52,539 --> 00:29:04,250
When you talk about this body, I think every, I don't know, I read it somewhere, but every atom

266
00:29:05,159 --> 00:29:09,747
is exchanged in your body something like every few days or something.

267
00:29:10,647 --> 00:29:14,054
It's quite remarkable how quickly the body is changing.

268
00:29:15,376 --> 00:29:18,501
The cornea on your eye changes every week.

269
00:29:19,723 --> 00:29:24,972
I know that for sure because the optician told me, and I believe the optician.

270
00:29:26,674 --> 00:29:33,623
I mean, if you look at, if you go into the biology of certain parts of your body, you'll be quite amazed how they're not actually in unison.

271
00:29:33,823 --> 00:29:35,284
Bits are falling off without you knowing.

272
00:29:36,385 --> 00:29:38,027
Bits take time to fall off.

273
00:29:38,047 --> 00:29:40,829
I mean, a bone, I think, takes about three months to renew itself.

274
00:29:41,770 --> 00:29:47,257
So even now, you walked into that door with this body, but it isn't this body anymore.

275
00:29:47,557 --> 00:29:48,317
It's moved on.

276
00:29:48,558 --> 00:29:49,199
It's changed.

277
00:29:49,219 --> 00:29:49,779
It's, you know...

278
00:29:51,835 --> 00:29:57,320
So this idea of a self, it has something static about it, it has something solid.

279
00:29:58,281 --> 00:29:59,182
This is what I am.

280
00:29:59,884 --> 00:30:08,933
But when we investigate the body, we find this am-ness can't be static.

281
00:30:08,953 --> 00:30:11,797
And if it's moving, if it's changing, then which am I?

282
00:30:12,396 --> 00:30:15,480
Am I the body that I was born with, or this body, or the future body?

283
00:30:16,182 --> 00:30:19,345
So the sense of I begins to corrupt, it begins to fall apart.

284
00:30:26,227 --> 00:30:28,288
But if I say I am the body, you can imagine.

285
00:30:28,449 --> 00:30:29,230
Well, we know, don't we?

286
00:30:29,250 --> 00:30:31,172
We know the suffering of I am the body.

287
00:30:31,731 --> 00:30:37,156
It comes out when you fall sick, when somebody close to you dies.

288
00:30:38,438 --> 00:30:44,144
Then you know, oh, well, if that body went that way, probably mine will follow in the same way.

289
00:30:46,346 --> 00:30:49,327
And we all dread the moment when the doctor will tell you you've got six weeks to go.

290
00:30:50,690 --> 00:30:53,112
That's not a laughing matter, is it?

291
00:30:56,669 --> 00:31:04,076
So this sense of self, this identity with the body, manifests when the body moves into danger.

292
00:31:06,057 --> 00:31:17,710
And that fear that we have, that real fear of death, of dying, of severe illness, of being crippled, of losing our minds, Alzheimer's, all that fear is the measure of that delusion.

293
00:31:24,036 --> 00:31:25,798
See, when the Buddha died, he...

294
00:31:27,060 --> 00:31:27,821
He was in pain.

295
00:31:27,942 --> 00:31:30,885
He had gastroenteritis or some sort.

296
00:31:30,905 --> 00:31:31,707
He would have been in pain.

297
00:31:33,430 --> 00:31:37,515
But by how it's come down to it, he's just lying on his side.

298
00:31:39,478 --> 00:31:44,625
And there's even still that desire to make sure that he's said everything.

299
00:31:44,644 --> 00:31:48,589
He asks, you know, are there any more questions?

300
00:31:48,609 --> 00:31:52,875
And when there are no more questions, he says, well, all compounded things arise and pass away.

301
00:31:53,537 --> 00:31:55,459
Work diligently for your liberation.

302
00:31:55,479 --> 00:31:56,140
And off he goes.

303
00:32:00,067 --> 00:32:02,551
What will be our last words?

304
00:32:04,435 --> 00:32:04,896
Why me?

305
00:32:08,262 --> 00:32:09,325
What will be our last thoughts?

306
00:32:09,345 --> 00:32:10,807
Will they be as equanimous as that?

307
00:32:10,886 --> 00:32:11,868
As easy?

308
00:32:11,909 --> 00:32:14,394
Will we let go as easy as that?

309
00:32:17,819 --> 00:32:21,006
So the reason we can't let go as easy as that is because it's what I think I am.

310
00:32:21,046 --> 00:32:23,410
I'm losing a bit of me.

311
00:32:28,839 --> 00:32:30,803
You think about your emotional life.

312
00:32:32,665 --> 00:32:33,748
That's changed, hasn't it?

313
00:32:33,768 --> 00:32:37,134
That's constantly changing, probably faster than the body's changing.

314
00:32:41,300 --> 00:32:49,535
All these intentions we make, all these, the way that we create this inner life within ourselves, all the depressions and anxieties, etc.

315
00:32:50,435 --> 00:32:53,801
And the happinesses, the loves and all those, the joys of life.

316
00:32:56,971 --> 00:32:58,333
They seem to come and go, don't they?

317
00:32:59,755 --> 00:33:01,336
And even more fleeting is thought.

318
00:33:01,696 --> 00:33:02,698
So which thought are you?

319
00:33:04,200 --> 00:33:07,565
And would you want to go back to being a three-year-old, the three-year-old's thoughts?

320
00:33:13,972 --> 00:33:19,619
So when we begin to investigate this self, this I am, this I am,

321
00:33:20,426 --> 00:33:30,183
And you finish it off, I am, I think therefore I am, I feel therefore I am, I walk around therefore I am, I brush my teeth therefore I am.

322
00:33:31,204 --> 00:33:39,479
When you investigate that as something solid, entire, whole unto itself, it begins to crumble, doesn't it?

323
00:33:39,499 --> 00:33:40,340
It begins to crumble.

324
00:33:43,165 --> 00:33:45,169
But we find that when we're in that state,

325
00:33:46,599 --> 00:33:59,511
What it makes us do is to hold on to the present moment tightly or make sure this present moment has some sort of sense to this ongoing feeling of self and it creates this future.

326
00:34:01,433 --> 00:34:02,575
You've got to be going somewhere.

327
00:34:05,137 --> 00:34:07,559
What's the point of just being here if you're not going somewhere?

328
00:34:08,981 --> 00:34:11,224
What's the point of meditating if you're not going to get some results?

329
00:34:12,625 --> 00:34:14,067
That's a hard one, isn't it?

330
00:34:14,086 --> 00:34:15,628
You've all come here for some result.

331
00:34:17,380 --> 00:34:18,141
Very disappointing.

332
00:34:31,833 --> 00:34:41,563
And this self, this becoming, this process of being me all the time, me all the time, is driven by this desire to be happy.

333
00:34:41,963 --> 00:34:42,744
That's what we want, isn't it?

334
00:34:42,764 --> 00:34:43,945
To be happy, for heaven's sake.

335
00:34:45,831 --> 00:34:49,697
I don't want to be rich, I just want to be happy.

336
00:34:53,644 --> 00:35:05,545
So being driven by this want to be happy, I've got to manipulate, I've got to actually struggle against the way things are to make me happy because my happiness is defined by what's made me happy in the past.

337
00:35:10,300 --> 00:35:15,525
If crumpets and cocoa have made me happy on Thursday, then next Thursday I've got to have crumpets and cocoa.

338
00:35:15,545 --> 00:35:16,126
I won't be happy.

339
00:35:17,268 --> 00:35:17,788
Simple as that.

340
00:35:23,695 --> 00:35:25,777
So I begin to try and manipulate the future.

341
00:35:25,797 --> 00:35:29,641
Now when we say the future, that's not some abstract idea.

342
00:35:29,702 --> 00:35:30,663
That means people.

343
00:35:30,682 --> 00:35:32,465
I've got to manipulate you to make me happy.

344
00:35:33,425 --> 00:35:35,188
If you get in my way, I've got to manipulate you.

345
00:35:35,208 --> 00:35:36,309
I've got to play around with you.

346
00:35:36,670 --> 00:35:38,492
If an object gets in my way, I kick it out.

347
00:35:38,572 --> 00:35:38,972
I burn it.

348
00:35:38,992 --> 00:35:39,733
I get rid of it.

349
00:35:49,652 --> 00:35:51,496
I mean, we have these ideologies, don't we?

350
00:35:52,077 --> 00:35:55,902
When a group of people take on a similar idea, you get these vast ideologies.

351
00:35:56,603 --> 00:35:59,389
Christianity, communism, capitalism.

352
00:36:00,010 --> 00:36:00,911
And you can see what it does.

353
00:36:02,414 --> 00:36:10,425
It destroys people because they all have to fit into this future idea, this thing that's created only in somebody's head.

354
00:36:11,547 --> 00:36:13,871
And if you don't fit in, well, you get shot.

355
00:36:17,041 --> 00:36:24,748
So it has our way, this self has a way of collecting other selves to support the idea this self has.

356
00:36:25,590 --> 00:36:27,411
And then you have a movement.

357
00:36:27,911 --> 00:36:28,492
Oh my goodness.

358
00:36:34,918 --> 00:36:36,900
That's what happens to religions, isn't it?

359
00:36:36,940 --> 00:36:45,309
From the first inspiration, it becomes locked into a series of beliefs and attitudes and then it becomes a movement, you know.

360
00:36:46,487 --> 00:36:49,996
And it loses that original spontaneity.

361
00:36:50,958 --> 00:36:55,750
And every so often a teacher comes along and sort of reforms it and you get that burst of energy again.

362
00:36:56,811 --> 00:37:02,184
But often it will just solidify into rites and rituals, customs.

363
00:37:03,277 --> 00:37:04,961
Rules and regulations.

364
00:37:06,083 --> 00:37:17,789
I mean, Jesus, you know, with the Jewish tradition, Sabbath was not made for, what is it, man was not made for the Sabbath, Sabbath was made for man.

365
00:37:18,411 --> 00:37:23,262
That's what he's saying, these rules and regulations are not there to bind us.

366
00:37:30,869 --> 00:37:43,679
So all these problems that we come across, all these conflicts, all the emotional turmoil, all of that, it all falls back on this I am.

367
00:37:46,072 --> 00:37:58,847
Now, that's the crucial importance of Vipassana meditation or these other forms, in other forms of Buddhism like Zen, Zazen or Dzogchen.

368
00:37:58,867 --> 00:38:04,034
It's all about getting down to that root level of the problem.

369
00:38:04,054 --> 00:38:14,427
Now, I often quote every evening, I quote this business of those who are mindful are in the presence of Nibbāna, in the vicinity of Nibbāna.

370
00:38:15,806 --> 00:38:16,728
So what do we mean by that?

371
00:38:17,389 --> 00:38:40,380
Well, when you sit still, and so you've steadied the body and stilled the body, and you've found this observation post within yourself, and you've become an observer within yourself, a feeler, an experiencer, and you're looking into the so-called self, this body, this psychophysical complex organism, you see,

372
00:38:41,896 --> 00:38:45,498
That's a very different position from, I am the body, isn't it?

373
00:38:45,518 --> 00:38:47,481
Because you're saying, there's the body.

374
00:38:49,483 --> 00:38:53,085
I mean, when somebody has a headache, they say, I have a headache, I am ill.

375
00:38:53,766 --> 00:39:01,632
But here, suddenly from this position, you're looking at the knee, you're feeling the knee, and you're saying, well, there's pain.

376
00:39:01,652 --> 00:39:11,581
There's somehow a separation, there's a gap has appeared between this knowing and what it knows.

377
00:39:12,760 --> 00:39:14,842
And that gap is a loss of self.

378
00:39:15,043 --> 00:39:17,246
It's a loss of a relationship.

379
00:39:17,545 --> 00:39:19,628
It's no longer my knee, my pain.

380
00:39:20,730 --> 00:39:21,952
It is, there's pain.

381
00:39:26,938 --> 00:39:34,148
When you have an emotion come up, you know, depression comes up, or joy, or some sort of excitement, or this dullness and lethargy.

382
00:39:35,068 --> 00:39:36,630
See, normally you'd say, I am tired.

383
00:39:37,251 --> 00:39:38,733
And that's good enough reason to go to bed.

384
00:39:40,925 --> 00:39:44,829
I am depressed, and that's a good enough reason to go to bed.

385
00:39:45,489 --> 00:39:48,873
Lots of amazing good reasons to go into bed, but here you can't.

386
00:39:48,893 --> 00:39:53,356
If I go to bed, no, I'll be very upset.

387
00:39:53,376 --> 00:39:54,518
You have to say, oh, there's dullness.

388
00:39:54,739 --> 00:39:56,119
There's dullness in the head.

389
00:39:56,179 --> 00:39:58,563
It feels like porridge.

390
00:39:58,583 --> 00:40:00,304
And there's tiredness in the body, you see.

391
00:40:01,565 --> 00:40:08,012
But somehow this there is has made whatever knows, that which knows, separate itself from

392
00:40:10,186 --> 00:40:11,788
It's formed a new relationship with it.

393
00:40:11,989 --> 00:40:12,409
It's not me.

394
00:40:12,429 --> 00:40:13,030
It's not mine.

395
00:40:13,431 --> 00:40:14,112
There is this.

396
00:40:17,456 --> 00:40:24,686
It's just like a property that you've sold or a car that you used to have that you've sold.

397
00:40:26,369 --> 00:40:28,152
You have a very different relationship to it, don't you?

398
00:40:28,172 --> 00:40:29,134
It's not yours anymore.

399
00:40:29,193 --> 00:40:29,934
It's somebody else's.

400
00:40:30,856 --> 00:40:36,565
The fact that all the pipes burst, well, you're very compassionate, but it's not your problem anymore, is it?

401
00:40:38,789 --> 00:40:41,775
But if it's your house, your car, it's very upsetting if things go wrong.

402
00:40:43,579 --> 00:40:52,981
So can you see that if we can develop a relationship with the body where this is the body, not me, not mine, when things go wrong, why should fear arise?

403
00:40:53,001 --> 00:40:53,802
It's not me, it's not mine.

404
00:40:55,005 --> 00:40:55,927
Why should I get depressed?

405
00:40:55,947 --> 00:40:56,949
It's not me, it's not mine.

406
00:41:04,202 --> 00:41:08,630
Emotions, you see, we find out that they're just these volitional conditionings.

407
00:41:08,710 --> 00:41:10,693
That's a sort of translation of the word sankhara.

408
00:41:11,173 --> 00:41:12,096
They're just conditionings.

409
00:41:13,818 --> 00:41:15,099
A mental conditioning.

410
00:41:15,701 --> 00:41:16,141
What is it?

411
00:41:16,181 --> 00:41:17,043
What is an emotion?

412
00:41:17,543 --> 00:41:19,907
What is it before you give it a name?

413
00:41:22,050 --> 00:41:26,277
So here you are, you're meditating and this feeling comes up.

414
00:41:28,385 --> 00:41:31,088
And you can see it's not a physical feeling like pain or pleasure.

415
00:41:31,889 --> 00:41:32,931
It's a mental feeling.

416
00:41:32,971 --> 00:41:35,916
It's more of a subtle sort of energy.

417
00:41:37,257 --> 00:41:45,989
And as you look into it, you say, oh, that feels like depression or feels like anxiety or it feels like joy, feels like excitement.

418
00:41:47,911 --> 00:41:51,998
But to do that, you must have separated yourself.

419
00:41:52,018 --> 00:41:54,021
To investigate something, you've got to be outside it.

420
00:41:55,722 --> 00:41:59,067
If you want to look at cells, you've got to find an instrument and you're looking at it.

421
00:42:00,889 --> 00:42:03,492
If you want to look up in the sky, you've got to get an instrument and you've got to look at it.

422
00:42:03,972 --> 00:42:05,755
You can't be the star.

423
00:42:05,775 --> 00:42:10,943
You can't get lost in some sort of romantic emotion if you want to study the star.

424
00:42:10,963 --> 00:42:14,748
So here, in order to find out what an emotion is, we've had to separate from it.

425
00:42:15,708 --> 00:42:21,257
And that separation, that distinction, is a loss of self because you're not saying anything.

426
00:42:21,608 --> 00:42:22,610
I am depressed.

427
00:42:23,090 --> 00:42:24,411
You're saying there is depression.

428
00:42:24,431 --> 00:42:26,315
You're not saying I am excited.

429
00:42:26,416 --> 00:42:32,244
There's excitement.

430
00:42:32,264 --> 00:42:36,851
And we can take this as far as thoughts and images.

431
00:42:36,871 --> 00:42:40,557
When you get into a really good quiet state, you can see a thought coming.

432
00:42:40,597 --> 00:42:42,902
You see an image beginning to grow.

433
00:42:43,141 --> 00:42:45,726
Sometimes a thought passes through your mind like a neon light.

434
00:42:47,545 --> 00:42:51,670
And when you have those sorts of experiences, you know, well, I didn't think that.

435
00:42:53,172 --> 00:42:54,394
It just arose and passed away.

436
00:42:59,001 --> 00:43:11,358
So, very slowly, through the practice of vipassana, we are distinguishing, we're finding out that, well, this is not what I am, this is not me, not mine.

437
00:43:11,795 --> 00:43:14,559
And that process, of course, leads us backwards.

438
00:43:14,918 --> 00:43:16,360
This is the unfortunate thing.

439
00:43:16,380 --> 00:43:18,103
You don't know where you're going.

440
00:43:19,726 --> 00:43:22,469
It leads us backwards to the knowledge of who I am.

441
00:43:31,601 --> 00:43:33,344
That's the koan.

442
00:43:33,364 --> 00:43:37,610
That's the big question, as I understand it anyway, of Korean Zen.

443
00:43:37,871 --> 00:43:38,291
It's just that.

444
00:43:38,711 --> 00:43:39,253
Who am I?

445
00:43:41,342 --> 00:43:46,813
And it's the moment after you've asked the question which is the potential moment.

446
00:43:46,994 --> 00:43:51,282
After that the mind rushes in to tell you who you are and what you are.

447
00:43:52,242 --> 00:43:53,927
But just to hang on in there, who am I?

448
00:43:54,226 --> 00:44:03,704
And that moment of not knowing has all the potential of breaking that essential delusion that hangs around the word I.

449
00:44:11,548 --> 00:44:29,894
So from the Buddha's teaching, this becoming, this constant becoming me, this arising out of one moment into the next, is the fundamental problem that is creating this wrong relationship with the world.

450
00:44:30,550 --> 00:44:32,351
And it puts us into a conflict with it.

451
00:44:32,871 --> 00:44:35,675
Whether it's a subtle conflict or a major conflict, it doesn't matter.

452
00:44:35,715 --> 00:44:36,695
It's always a conflict.

453
00:44:36,715 --> 00:44:42,041
Because we're always trying to manipulate things to fit in with this sense of me.

454
00:44:46,865 --> 00:44:50,329
Now when that goes, there's a whole new relationship.

455
00:44:51,130 --> 00:44:52,190
Now there is no future.

456
00:44:53,353 --> 00:44:54,112
There's no past.

457
00:44:54,673 --> 00:44:56,155
You're not coming from a fixed position.

458
00:44:56,356 --> 00:44:57,856
You're not going to a fixed position.

459
00:45:00,217 --> 00:45:17,045
Our ability will be to be completely receptive, without any sieve, without any separation of what we don't want, what we don't like.

460
00:45:19,289 --> 00:45:22,494
And in that, there's that very open communication.

461
00:45:25,123 --> 00:45:43,385
And in that open, immediate communication, whether it be with a person or with an animal or with just nature, with a tree, just an openness to a tree, to a leaf, there's that sense of just being here in a very total way, for no other reason than just to be here.

462
00:45:50,268 --> 00:45:52,690
And with it there arises just a natural joy.

463
00:45:52,731 --> 00:45:54,773
This is what the Buddha says, just a natural joy.

464
00:45:55,134 --> 00:46:04,385
That contentment is that being with the moment, not wanting anything more than what the moment is giving us.

465
00:46:07,389 --> 00:46:10,271
And the happiness comes out of the response to that moment.

466
00:46:12,135 --> 00:46:13,356
Contentment and happiness.

467
00:46:32,505 --> 00:46:33,407
So that's where we're going.

468
00:46:34,088 --> 00:46:38,137
And we should be happier.

469
00:46:38,157 --> 00:46:40,342
That's what we mean by hope as opposed to expectation.

470
00:46:41,304 --> 00:46:52,347
Hope is the knowledge, that inner knowledge, that inner feeling, that intuitive understanding that there's an end to suffering.

471
00:46:53,469 --> 00:46:53,568
Yeah.

472
00:46:56,653 --> 00:46:58,657
There's an end to that wrong sort of relationship.

473
00:46:58,958 --> 00:47:04,525
And what the vipassana practice is doing is making us see that, yeah, there's a possibility of an end to this.

474
00:47:07,451 --> 00:47:13,380
It doesn't make it any easier, but it does lift the practice a bit to know that there is an end to suffering.

475
00:47:17,257 --> 00:47:17,858
No.

476
00:47:19,362 --> 00:47:24,052
See, becoming has to have this objective.

477
00:47:24,954 --> 00:47:28,541
Becoming has to have this expectancy, which is slightly different.

478
00:47:34,193 --> 00:47:37,139
Making a distinction between hope and expectation.

479
00:47:38,284 --> 00:47:42,610
Hope is a fundamental position to life, that life is good.

480
00:47:43,391 --> 00:47:44,193
It has meaning.

481
00:47:45,014 --> 00:47:49,119
There is a reason for suffering.

482
00:47:53,126 --> 00:47:55,449
And the reason for suffering is this wrong relationship.

483
00:47:55,789 --> 00:48:01,677
And that once the wrong relationship is corrected, happiness, perfect peace, all that arises.

484
00:48:04,001 --> 00:48:06,385
Expectation would want to put a date on it.

485
00:48:07,782 --> 00:48:11,068
The expectation would want to achieve it.

486
00:48:11,809 --> 00:48:15,376
But what we realize in the meditation is that it's not achievable by you.

487
00:48:15,436 --> 00:48:18,221
That's another thing that you recognize, isn't it?

488
00:48:18,521 --> 00:48:19,983
That it happens.

489
00:48:20,003 --> 00:48:23,690
Once you find yourself in that position, the heart begins to purify itself.

490
00:48:23,710 --> 00:48:24,572
You don't have to do anything.

491
00:48:24,733 --> 00:48:26,094
It's like the body heals itself.

492
00:48:37,246 --> 00:48:39,228
You can't have a spiritual insight.

493
00:48:39,248 --> 00:48:42,452
You can't say, well, I'm going to sit down now and I'm going to have a spiritual insight.

494
00:48:42,974 --> 00:48:43,574
You can't do it.

495
00:48:44,615 --> 00:48:45,597
You can have an intellectual insight.

496
00:48:45,617 --> 00:48:48,161
You can think about something.

497
00:48:48,181 --> 00:48:49,181
You can have an aesthetic insight.

498
00:48:49,202 --> 00:48:53,088
You can set yourself a task to understand something aesthetically or that way.

499
00:48:54,188 --> 00:48:55,510
But you can't make yourself have an insight.

500
00:48:55,550 --> 00:49:03,422
In fact, you might argue that when it comes to certain problems, even insights of that nature are beyond the self.

501
00:49:04,903 --> 00:49:08,557
You know, scientists will talk about how the answer just came.

502
00:49:08,777 --> 00:49:09,460
They'll go to sleep.

503
00:49:09,681 --> 00:49:13,255
They'll sleep on an answer, you know, and then they wake up with it.

504
00:49:14,398 --> 00:49:16,467
Who thought that one out?

505
00:49:23,112 --> 00:49:31,139
So how do we bring ourselves, how do we begin to train ourselves in daily life to get this sense of being rather than becoming?

506
00:49:33,181 --> 00:49:36,826
And the trick there is to really get your intentions right.

507
00:49:38,226 --> 00:49:40,989
So when you're eating, you're just eating to nourish the body.

508
00:49:41,349 --> 00:49:43,052
You're not asking for it to make you happy.

509
00:49:43,692 --> 00:49:44,293
It's as simple as that.

510
00:49:44,313 --> 00:49:48,257
If you're asking for it to make you happy, then you've formed a different relationship with food.

511
00:49:49,297 --> 00:49:52,460
But if the food is there just as medicine for the body, what's the problem?

512
00:49:53,588 --> 00:49:57,014
The fact that it tastes nice is a plus, a little gift.

513
00:49:59,637 --> 00:50:20,911
When you want to help somebody, make sure that your intention is right, that you're just doing it for that person, you're just doing it out of the goodness of heart, that there's no subliminal reasons for doing it, that you want your kitchen decorated too and that you expect them to come along and do it, things like that.

514
00:50:23,929 --> 00:50:29,516
When you do whatever job you do to get it right, that you're doing it as a service, of course there's pay.

515
00:50:30,677 --> 00:50:33,621
And of course there's hopefully the enjoyment of the job.

516
00:50:34,001 --> 00:50:36,164
But those are to be seen as merit.

517
00:50:36,585 --> 00:50:38,507
We have this idea in Buddhism of merit.

518
00:50:39,467 --> 00:50:45,195
You get merit, you get something added on because of your good heart.

519
00:50:46,576 --> 00:50:53,244
So the merit of doing your job is you get a wage and you get a certain joy out of it.

520
00:50:53,264 --> 00:50:54,626
But that's not why you're doing it.

521
00:50:56,068 --> 00:50:58,349
The reason we should be doing work is out of a service.

522
00:50:59,632 --> 00:51:00,914
You're doing it for the benefit of the other.

523
00:51:03,617 --> 00:51:07,481
It doesn't get rid of the idea of ambition.

524
00:51:07,842 --> 00:51:11,166
You don't have to not be ambitious because you've decided to live the spiritual life.

525
00:51:13,340 --> 00:51:21,429
But your attitude is, well, these are the talents I've got and I can see that a job, I could do that job, so I'll offer these talents as a service.

526
00:51:23,311 --> 00:51:28,916
So if you find that somebody else got the job, you know, there's not that disappointment.

527
00:51:30,860 --> 00:51:31,539
Because it was an offering.

528
00:51:31,599 --> 00:51:32,882
It's like, you know, you give a present.

529
00:51:33,523 --> 00:51:37,186
I mean, if you give a present and the person says, well, it's all right, no, I don't want it.

530
00:51:37,226 --> 00:51:38,367
You shouldn't feel bad about it, should you?

531
00:51:40,255 --> 00:51:44,702
You only feel bad about it because there's some ego, there's some self involved in the giving of the present.

532
00:51:45,043 --> 00:51:46,626
It's like they've not accepted you.

533
00:51:48,269 --> 00:51:49,331
You've been rejected.

534
00:51:51,195 --> 00:51:52,177
So you feel dejected.

535
00:51:54,782 --> 00:52:03,056
So in terms of our meditation, we're trying to make this distinction as to what is me and what is not me.

536
00:52:06,039 --> 00:52:14,668
And mainly the technique is to see not me, not me, not mine, not me, not mine.

537
00:52:14,688 --> 00:52:23,898
And then when we go out into daily life to see, to be aware of any selfish, any self-centered intention.

538
00:52:24,778 --> 00:52:25,760
Now you've got to be careful here.

539
00:52:26,280 --> 00:52:29,663
There's a difference between selfishness and self-regard, self-care.

540
00:52:29,702 --> 00:52:31,304
I mean sometimes you've got to look after yourself.

541
00:52:36,364 --> 00:52:41,532
But in terms of what you're doing, you're doing it with the right attitude for the benefit of the other.

542
00:52:42,092 --> 00:52:43,635
So there are three positions.

543
00:52:43,735 --> 00:52:50,925
You do things for your own benefit, you do things for the benefit of the other, and you do things both for your own benefit and the benefit of the other.

544
00:52:51,485 --> 00:52:53,068
That's how the Buddha sort of states it.

545
00:52:57,313 --> 00:52:58,695
And then you see the result, you see.

546
00:52:58,896 --> 00:53:03,402
Not the result out there, because you never know what happens when you do something out there, you know.

547
00:53:05,963 --> 00:53:07,206
But you see the result inside.

548
00:53:08,829 --> 00:53:09,891
Has it caused attachment?

549
00:53:10,132 --> 00:53:11,255
Has it caused disappointment?

550
00:53:11,876 --> 00:53:16,327
If anything negative comes up from an action, then you know there's something crept in there.

551
00:53:35,831 --> 00:53:41,539
So let's presume that that little girl who said there's no reason for being is already there.

552
00:53:41,898 --> 00:53:46,184
She might be fully and completely liberated.

553
00:53:49,347 --> 00:53:49,927
You never know.

554
00:53:56,094 --> 00:53:58,878
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

555
00:53:59,639 --> 00:54:04,405
May you be liberated sooner rather than later.

